---
---

<section data-test="problem-section" id="problem" style="padding: 4rem 1.5rem; background-color: var(--bg-primary);">
  <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h2 data-test="problem-heading" style="font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.25rem); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); text-align: center; margin: 0 0 1rem;">
      Why Existing Spec Approaches Fail
    </h2>
    <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.05rem; margin: 0 0 3rem; max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
      Most specification methods were designed for human developers. They produce artifacts that AI agents struggle to interpret, leading to misbuilt features and costly rework.
    </p>
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem;">
      {[
        { icon: '📄', title: 'Too Vague', body: 'User stories like "the user should be able to log in" leave implementation details entirely to interpretation.' },
        { icon: '🌀', title: 'No Hierarchy', body: 'Flat requirements lists have no structure. An AI agent has no way to understand which decisions constrain others.' },
        { icon: '🔀', title: 'Untestable', body: 'Requirements written without acceptance criteria cannot be validated automatically — you\'re stuck manual testing forever.' },
        { icon: '💸', title: 'Expensive to Fix', body: 'When an AI builds the wrong thing, you pay twice: once to build it wrong, once to rebuild it right.' },
      ].map(({ icon, title, body }) => (
        <div style="background-color: var(--bg-card); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 0.75rem; padding: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">{icon}</div>
          <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin: 0 0 0.5rem;">{title}</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">{body}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
